Lists are a great way to organize your information, and this is also true with websites, since the reader needs to see the data displayed in a systematic, organized manner.
So in HTML we have different tags which help in organising the data 


•	Unordered List: An unordered list starts with the “ul” tag. Each list item starts with the “li” tag. The list items are marked with bullets i.e small black circles by default.

Example –

 
Code 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  
<body>
    <h1>Games </h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Cricket</li>
        <li>Hockey</li>
        <li>BasketBall</li>
        <li>Table Tennis</li>
    </ul>
</body>
  
</html>


In CSS, list-style-type defines the markup for the list item. The value can either be: disc, square ,circle , none 

Code-

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  
<body>
    <ul style="list-style-type:disc;">
        <li>Cricket</li>
        <li>Hockey</li>
        <li>BasketBall</li>
        <li>Table Tennis</li>
      </ul>
      <ul style="list-style-type:circle;">
        <li>Cricket</li>
        <li>Hockey</li>
        <li>BasketBall</li>
        <li>Table Tennis</li>
      </ul>
      <ul style="list-style-type:square;">
        <li>Cricket</li>
        <li>Hockey</li>
        <li>BasketBall</li>
        <li>Table Tennis</li>
      </ul>
      <ul style="list-style-type:none;">
        <li>Cricket</li>
        <li>Hockey</li>
        <li>BasketBall</li>
        <li>Table Tennis</li>
      </ul>
</body>
  
</html>

 

 Nested lists are also known as lists within lists. Nested lists appear as an element of another list.

Code-
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<body>
    <h1>Nested  List</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Fruits</li>
        <ul>
            <li>Apple</li>
            <li>Banana </li>
            <li>orange</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Cloud Services</li>
        <ul>
            <li>Google Cloud</li>
            <li>Azure</li>
            <li>AWS</li>
        </ul>
</body>

</html>


 

Ordered List

 An ordered list starts with the "ol" tag. Each list item is preceded by a "li" tag. The list items are marked with numbers by default. 
 
Code  

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <h1>Ordered List</h1>
    <ol type="1">
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
      </ol>
      <ol type="A">
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
      </ol>
      <ol type="a">
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
      </ol>
      <ol type="I">
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
      </ol>
      <ol type="i">
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
      </ol>      
</body>

</html>



Description lists 
  Description lists contain a list of terms, each with a description. The <dl> tag defines the description list, the tag defines the term name, and the tag describes the term  

Code –
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <h1>Description Lists</h1>
    <dl>
        <dt>Aristotle </dt>
        <dd>a Greek philosopher and polymath during the Classical period in Ancient Greece</dd>
        <dt>Charles Darwin</dt>
        <dd>English naturalist, geologist and biologist, best known for his contributions to
             the science of evolution.</dd>
      </dl>
</body>

</html>


 
